<DOC><DOCNO> AP891225-0111 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-25-89 2310EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Hostages-Waite     12-25 0187</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Hostages-Waite,0191</SECOND><HEAD>Bani-Sadr Says Waite In Hands Of Iranian Secret Service</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Iran's former president, Abolhassan Bani-Sadr, saidMonday he believes Iranian secret service agents are holdingBritish hostage Terry Waite, either in Lebanon or Iran.   Bani-Sadr, who was the Islamic Republic's first president buthas lived in exile in France since 1981, said in an interview thatfriends in Iran told him Waite had been ``in a safe place, insecurity for several months in the hands of the Iranian secretservices.''   He said he believed this could be a sign that negotiations forrelease of Waite and other Western hostages seized in Lebanon couldbe making progress.   Waite, 50, the special envoy of Archbishop of Canterbury RobertRuncie, disappeared in Beirut on Jan. 20, 1987, while on a missionto try to free Western hostages.   No group has claimed to hold him, but he is widely believed tobe held by Islamic Jihad.   Waite is one of 18 Western hostages in Lebanon. Longest held isAmerican Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent for TheAssociated Press, who was abducted March 16, 1985.</TEXT></DOC>